<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): Buoyant glass-maker shines - The
week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TUESDAY: The strong profit recovery at Pilkington, the glass maker, has
continued in the six months to September with analysts forecasting a figure
of between Pounds 45m and Pounds 55m before tax and exceptional items, up
from Pounds 30.5m in the first half of last year.
The improvement stems largely from increased capacity utilisation and some
price rises. The headline figure will be nearer Pounds 75m, including the
gain from the sale in June of its insulation business.
TUESDAY: After seeing promising first-quarter figures from Thorn EMI, the
music and rentals group, analysts are anticipating another encouraging set
of results. Jeffrey Harwood, leisure analyst at Robert Fleming Securities,
expects a 17 per cent pre-tax profits rise to Pounds 135m for the half to
September 30, against Pounds 115m.
Thorn has benefited from the bouyant state of the music business and is now
re-orienting its rental interests by moving into the burgeoning 'option to
buy' market.
TUESDAY: National Grid is expected to report pre-tax profits of about Pounds
300m (Pounds 285m) when it reports results for the first six months. The
City will be looking for as much information as possible on the Grid's
flotation, which is expected in the middle of the year, but it could have to
wait some weeks before details are announced.
TUESDAY: Interim profits at Northern Foods are forecast at around Pounds
65m, down from Pounds 72.1m a year earlier, because of pressure on dairy
profits, and exceptionals. Any indication of Northern's ideas for
restructuring the dairy industry would be welcomed by analysts.
TUESDAY: Vodafone, the UK's largest cellular phone group, is expected to
report interim pre-tax profits in the Pounds 175m-Pounds 185m range, only a
few percentage points ahead of last year's Pounds 174.5m, as start-up costs
for overseas licences start to bite. Overseas losses could amount to Pounds
50m. The UK cellular market has proved buoyant, however, with surprisingly
stable pricing, and it is expected that the bare figures conceal substantial
underlying growth.
WEDNESDAY: Courtaulds, the chemicals and fibres group whose shares have been
weak over the past few months, is expected to report interim profits before
exceptional items of around Pounds 80m, little changed from last year. But a
modest increase in the dividend to about 4.2p (4.0p) is thought likely. The
City will be keen to hear if Courtaulds is managing to pass on its rising
raw materials costs, which accelerated over the summer.
WEDNESDAY: Tate &amp; Lyle is expected to report pre-tax profits for the year
ended September of around Pounds 265m, against Pounds 223.5m a year earlier.
A recovery in cereal sweeteners and starches will be the main factor. A 1p
rise in full-year dividend to 14p is expected.
WEDNESDAY: Yorkshire Water is forecast to show a 12 per cent increase in
interim pre-tax profits before exceptionals to about Pounds 84m. The figures
will be overshadowed by restructuring provisions and accounting changes on
the treatment of infrastructure maintenance charges.
Shareholders will also be curious to know whether Yorkshire has been tempted
to follow the trend of higher-than-expected dividend payments. Forecasts are
for at least an 8 per cent increase to 8.2p, which could well be bettered.
WEDNESDAY: Granada Group, the broadcasting, leisure, rental and business
services group, is expected to report pre-tax profits for the year to
end-September of at least Pounds 250m on Wednesday, up from Pounds 176m last
time. The second half will see the first full contribution from London
Weekend Television, of which Granada won control in February for Pounds
760m.
THURSDAY: After last month's upbeat trading statement, the City expects a
good set of interim results from retailer Storehouse.
Analysts forecast pre-tax profits of around Pounds 25m, compared with Pounds
11.6m last time, for the group which includes British Home Stores,
Mothercare and Blazer. Attention is likely to focus on how well the BHS
expansion programme is progressing.
THURSDAY: Allied Domecq is expected to report interim pre-tax profits of
around Pounds 240m after exceptionals and Pounds 310m before, against Pounds
271m and Pounds 292m respectively a year earlier. A dividend increase of
around 6 per cent to 7.5p a share is likely.
Investors will be looking for more news on the integration of Domecq into
the group and on further recovery at Carlsberg Tetley, the group's beer
joint venture which lost market share last year.
</TEXT>
