<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: Inside the pyramid game - The respectable
name is multi-level marketing and the bait is unlimited income. But Bethan
Hutton finds that dreams can be shattered all too easily
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The function room in a smart Kensington hotel is full of well-dressed,
well-groomed people. The buzz of conversation dies down as the first speaker
steps to the front. 'You are looking for people who are looking for
something,' he says.
Each person in the audience is urged to think about who might be recruited.
Each is told to make a list of them - with at least 100 names on each list.
'Don't pre-judge anybody,' exhorts the speaker. 'Put them all down. Everyone
you can think of.'
It sounds like an an evangelical recruitment drive but the meeting was
actually organised by a large international organisation called Amway (an
abbreviation of the 'American way'). And, rather than being some hellfire
gospel church, the talk is of presenting business opportunities, not saving
souls.
Neither does the speaker have the American twang you might expect. His name
is Bris Bovill, he describes himself as a Warwickshire farmer, and his
accent has the cut-glass tones of the English upper-class.
Bovill and his wife, Kerry, joined Amway 3 1/2 years ago. They started
selling cleaning products, toiletries and make-up to family and friends,
taking a cut on the selling price while recruiting people to become Amway
distributors themselves.
With Amway's multi-level marketing system - also known as pyramid selling -
the real money comes not from selling many products but from the commission
you earn on sales made by people you recruit and those that they recruit,
right down a long line.
Now, Bris and Kerry have reached the highest level on the pyramid. They have
become 'diamond distributors', people whose incomes can be well into six
figures. They recruited about 30 people personally but there are hundreds
more 'down-line' from them.
A recent edition of Amway's company magazine, Amagram, celebrated the
Bovills' achievements with glossy photographs of their farm in Warwickshire
and elegant house full of antiques. But these are not the trappings of
success with Amway; they were paid for with much older money.
'I didn't have any material goals,' says Bris. 'I think I had everything I
wanted. But, without the business, I would still be sitting on my tractor,
probably. I would have convinced myself I didn't want to travel.' Now, the
farm work has been contracted out so that the Bovills can concentrate on
Amway.
Yet, their success is exceptional. While Amway has about 33,000 distributors
in the UK, only a dozen are in the highest-earning 'diamond' class. For
most, Amway provides a little extra cash - but not enough to live on.
The unemployed or genuinely hard-up tend not to do well in multi-level
marketing schemes like this, either. They are too obviously needy, lacking
the panache and self-confidence to inspire others to join.
Bovill's spiel at the Kensington hotel illustrates the kind of needs Amway
aims to fulfil. 'What would you do with an extra Pounds 100 a month?' he
asks. The suggestions come back: a night at a Park Lane hotel, a day out at
the races followed by dinner, scuba-diving lessons, a new camera . . .
What about Pounds 1,000 a month? More diving lessons, holidays, investments,
a bigger house. One woman wants a horse to take eventing. These are not
people trying to make ends meet; they want to fund the little luxuries in
life - or, indeed, the larger ones.
Amway people always keep their ears open for new recruits. They make a
mental note of casual complaints at dinner parties about the size of school
fees, or not being able to afford a skiing holiday.
Talking business on social occasions is discouraged, but leads are followed
up with a telephone call a day or two later. 'I heard what you said about
school fees the other day, and I have an idea that may be of interest to you
. . . '
Then, a meeting is arranged to demonstrate the Amway business plan - a
complicated series of flip-charts with diagrams showing how you can build up
a business paying Pounds 45,000 a year from an initial outlay of Pounds 70.
Amway's is by no means the only business plan being demonstrated in living
rooms across the country. Companies selling water filters, costume jewellery
and security equipment are among those using very similar techniques.
Becoming an Amway distributor seems to be a cross between becoming an Avon
lady, a born-again Christian and a member of the Rotary Club. But all sorts
of sensible, respectable people are doing it. Amagram is full of them:
smiling couples - teachers, housewives, antique dealers, management
consultants, dentists - who have achieved pearl or ruby distributor status.
Yet, behind the happy faces in the company magazine lurk some less
heart-warming stories. Friends of Amway converts say it can take over
people's lives like a cult. Some become so obsessed that they eat, sleep and
breathe nothing else. They spend every waking moment trying to recruit new
people or working on their business plans. Their savings disappear on
motivational books and tapes.
Hints that perhaps Amway is taking up too much of their lives are met with
hostility. A few put emotional pressure on friends and relatives to buy
products or sign up as a distributor, just to help them meet this month's
target. Eventually, exhaustion and repeated rejections tend to shatter the
dream.
'This is not a get-rich-quick scheme,' Bovill tells his audience. Everyone
at Amway repeats that message. But when, in the next breath, they mention
unlimited potential income, people earning so much that they pay Pounds
150,000 a year in tax, trips to five-star hotels in Cyprus for top
performers - it is, perhaps, hardly surprising that a few 'people who are
looking for something' take it all too seriously.
Pyramid blueprints, Page 11
</TEXT>
<XX>
