<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / International Company News: Overseas demand boosts Honda's
first-half profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Honda, the Japanese carmaker, more than doubled pre-tax profits in the first
half in spite of disappointing domestic performance. It was lifted by strong
sales in North America and Europe, cost-cutting measures, and the sale of
its stake in Rover, the UK carmaker.
This was the first time in four years that Honda was able to report a rise
in profits, the group said. The outlook for the second-half performance was
even better as car sales in Japan in the latter half were expected to
recover, it added.
In the six months to September, Honda enjoyed buoyant demand in the North
American and European markets which supported a 6 per cent rise in group
revenues to Y1,991.4bn (Dollars 20.3bn) from a previous Y1,874.8bn.
Recurring profits - before extraordinary items and tax - more than doubled
to Y56.7bn from Y22.5bn previously, although the figure was helped by a
Y14.6bn gain on the sale of Honda's 20 per cent share in Rover, acquired by
BMW of Germany. Net income more than tripled to Y38bn from a previous
Y9.3bn, also helped by a Y12.8bn gain from the Rover sale.
In Europe, Honda's sales were supported by an increase in output of UK-made
Accords during the period and imports of US-made Civics. As a result, Honda
was able to maintain price competitiveness against other Japanese carmakers
in the region and became the only Japanese manufacturer to increase market
share in Europe, Honda said.
In the period from January to the end of October, 29 per cent, or 44,700
units, of the 153,500 vehicles Honda sold in Europe were manufactured in the
UK, it said. This figure would increase further when Honda started
manufacturing its European Civic model in the UK next year.
In contrast to its strong performance in North America and Europe, Honda
continued to suffer in the Japanese market during the period with unit sales
falling 5 per cent.
Honda forecasts full-year consolidated sales of Y3,991.4bn against
Y3,862.7bn, and net profits of Y60bn, against Y23.7bn last year and an
earlier forecast of Y52bn.
</TEXT>
