<DOCNO>FT944-8528</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKTAWAB8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Letters to the Editor: An educational challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr J G C LANDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In his article 'The old school lie' (November 10), John Authers's
comment, 'Parents place increasing weight on exam results', attracted my
attention. As parents who have sacrificed holidays abroad, etc, to finance
education, our aim has been to prepare our children for life rather than
just university entrance. My wife and I want our children to be successful
with their relationships with others as well as contributing with their
professional expertise.
As an employer I do not look for the candidate with the highest academic
achievement, I seek the candidate who will achieve the results I need. This
often requires a range of qualities, particularly those dealing with people
successfully - customers, suppliers, subordinates, peers and others.
May I challenge the FT to produce surveys showing the value of schools in
producing contributors to our community while at the same time leading
rewarding and happy lives.
J G C Lander,
Waterdale House,
Chequers Lane,
Waterdale, Watford,
Hertfordshire WD2 7LP
</TEXT>
