<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / Mobile phone price war fear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hong Kong is to go ahead with plans to issue up to 10 new mobile telephone
licences, despite criticism from existing providers and analysts that the
move could lead to price wars and lower standards of service. The decision,
yesterday, follows a lengthy consultation process that began when industry
views were solicited in February. Hong Kong has no bars on foreign
ownership, and since the proposal to expand the market was first mooted, big
industry players from across the world have made exploratory trips to the
colony. More than 100 application documents were handed out after the
announcement. The telecommunications Authority will decide on the number of
licences to be issued.
