<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: Counter voice - Making fun of fashion is no
longer fun because everybody's doing it
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It should no longer surprise anyone that fashion can have its own way with
history. Last month's Milan collections plundered the teenage innocence of
1950s Americana - pink satin preppy blouses, marabou powder puffs,
rhinestones and sequins - and gleefully married it to a sleazy 1970s catwalk
soundtrack (Barry White, Roxy Music and Gloria Gaynor) without so much as a
second thought.
It is not only textures and fabrics which today's designers feel able to mix
and match, it is entire decades and sensibilities, all helping to give a
'feel' to a new collection; and in the Italy of the 1990s, crocked by
corruption and cynicism, what better way of brightening the national mood
than this panchronistic explosion of fun and glamour?
Fashion is far from unique in this regard; the history of art in Western
culture is a long, interminable cycle of stolen ideas, fads and hommages to
distant cultures. Music and literature, too, frequently refer to their own
histories. But fushion's recycling of past glories is distinguished by the
sheer speed of reinvention. Technological innovation and the demands of the
mass media enable a trend to bloom, wither and die in less than 12 months.
Some, it might be said, do not even deserve to last that long. When
designers first raided the 1970s, barely 20 years after the original
version, many observers could hardly believe their eyes; this, after all,
was the decade which taste forgot, the era of tragic haircuts,
sprained-ankle footwear and flapping loons, its garish ghastliness captured
exquisitely by Clodagh Rodgers and her hot pants strutting their sorry stuff
at the Eurovision Song Contest. Surely they could not come back?
The answer from the streets was: why ever not? For as the style nightmare
has been enthusiastically relived over the past couple of years, it has
become increasingly apparent that traditional notions of good and bad taste
simply do not apply any longer; indeed, that the very notion of bringing
aesthetic judgment to bear on how we look is being satirised by the new
generation of plunderers. Looking good has taken a back seat to making fun.
It seems that in fashion, as in so many other areas, the post-modern
sensibility, revelling in the fragmented and the multi-focal, mocking
seriousness with its unrelenting tone of playful irony, has taken over. Good
taste is yesterday's phrase (prompting the thought that it may itself come
back into vogue tomorrow); but for the moment, anything goes.
No figure has better encapsulated the triumph of the post-modern, ironic
outlook than Franco Moschino, the Italian designer who died in September.
Where his contemporaries bedecked their garments with accessories or
carefully modulated patterns, Moschino instead chose self-mocking slogans:
'Waist of Money' flouted one waistline; 'A Shirt For Fashion Victims Only'
teased another.
Needless to say, the joke comes expensive, but it is not clear who is its
perpetrator and who is its victim. Those wearing the garments can reassure
themselves that they are 'in' on the jest, but that is not how an outside
observer might see it. Certainly the quest for beauty, the traditional aim
of all who work in the visual and design arts, is being endlessly deferred
in a bewildering, multi-layered comic conspiracy.
Moschino's supporters have applauded his work on the grounds that it brought
much-needed fun to a business which had become full of itself. In this
respect, today's post-modern viewpoint mirrors the camp sensibility that
exerted such an influence on earlier generations' tastes.
In her powerful essay Notes on Camp, written 30 years ago, Susan Sontag
spoke of the 'love of the exaggerated, the 'off', of
things-being-what-they-are-not', which can also be seen in much of today's
fashion.
Sontag quoted approvingly Oscar Wilde's observation that a doorknob could be
as admirable as a painting, as a shrewd anticipation of the 'democratic
esprit' of camp. Both of them would surely have joined Moschino in poking
fun at the po-faced, high-blown pretentions of haute couture.
And yet, there are differences between the social context in which Sontag
wrote her essay and that of today. In putting forward an intellectual
justification for camp, Sontag emphasised its role as a counter-balance to
the pervading mood of moral seriousness. 'Camp is a solvent of morality,'
she wrote. 'It neutralises moral indignation, sponsors playfulness.
'Camp taste is, above all, a mode of enjoyment, of appreciation - not
judgment. Camp is generous. It wants to enjoy.'
In the US of the early 1960s, when Notes on Camp was written, one would
surely have taken Sontag's point. Here was a society heaving with the strain
of cold war politics, still grieving over the brutal assassination of its
president, and forced to reassess its core values after the civil rights
marches and the challenges they posed to the country's constitution.
It was an intense time, and Sontag's celebration of Wilde, of witty
hedonism, of Camp's 'comic vision of the world', were in sharp contrast and
relief to the earnest mood of passionate debate which dominated the country
(as was the growth of Pop Art and the sillier counter-cultural movements of
the decade's later years).
It is hard to detect any of that moral gravity in today's prevailing
climate. In the US and Europe, post-modern politics, philosophy and art,
basking in ambiguity and relativism, dancing on the graves of the century's
dominant ideologies, have undermined the desire for morally committed
debate.
Camp, irony, playfulness have become the norm - no longer are they suspended
in a balance against the more stolid virtues of moral certitude and
argumentative rigour. Fun works best as an antidote to solemnity. The very
last thing we need in 1994 is to chuckle knowingly at a funny frock on the
catwalk. If society-at-large cannot be serious, perhaps we might look at the
masterful cut of a sumptuous fabric to take the lead
</TEXT>
