<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: The route of the suit - The man's suit
today may seem impervious to fashion's whims, but it has taken two centuries
of nipping and tucking to shape. James Ferguson traces its evolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES FERGUSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the Concise History of 20th Century Costume comes to be written, the
chapter on men could be distilled into one word. Suit. What the doublet and
hose were to the 16th century, the periwig to the 17th, cocked hat to the
18th and frock coat to the 19th, so the business suit will be to the 20th: a
symbol for its age.
The first office suit - the 'lounge' or 'suit of dittoes' of the 1880s - was
originally tweedy country wear for the man of means. This was an adaptation
of the workwear that the lowly bumpkin had been toiling in for a good
hundred years. Slowly it started sneaking into town, mingling with the frock
coat, and by 1900 every clerk was wearing one. It was as drab a costume as
there had ever been. Fashioned from sagging, sweaty serge, the jacket was
fastened so high that the shirt to be seen at all - required a
throat-slicing, four-inch-high, starched linen cylinder of a collar, jamming
the head into the era's equally uncompromising black bowler hat.
Men's fashion is rarely a sprint - it's a long-distance event, and the
lounge suit was no slouch. Having developed from the sporting and military
garb of the early 19th century, it turned out to have hidden stamina. It
just needed getting into shape.
The legs in particular had to be worked on. Trousers, or pantaloons, had
replaced kneebreeches in the years after Waterloo and had settled into the
19th century foot-strapped and braced, harnessing a man like a horse. But in
about 1880, spats on shoes appeared and creases were introduced on to the
sides of trousers. Then turn-ups came in, inspired by sport - ever the R&amp;D
department of men's fashion - where men were rolling up their hems to avoid
the mud on race tracks. And, finally, the invention of the trouser press in
the 1890s allowed full-length front and back creases and turn-ups proper.
So, by 1910, modern trousers were up and running.
Next, the jacket, which had too much flab round its middle. In 1912 a
post-Edwardian Scissorhands discovered that two vertical darts, one above
each hip pocket, did what the horizontal waist seam had been doing for the
frock coat and morning coat - that is, gave it shape. Now, bespoke tailors
could render the jacket elegant enough for their top-drawer clients, whom
everybody else would surely follow. The lounge suit was in business.
It soon shouldered aside the morning coat, which had already jostled the
frock coat on to the sidelines of posh weddings, horse races and pompous
state occasions. (The frock coat has since been reduced to funeral wear,
while the morning coat turns out gamely for Ascot and costumey weddings.)
Even the star of evening events, the tail coat, found itself elbowed into
head waiterdom by that lounge for lounge lizards: the dinner jacket.
By the 1920s pleats had been developed in trousers, giving the front crease
somewhere to go and enabling quantities of cloth to be folded under the
waistband. Consequently, Oxord bags were invented in 1924. They helped blow
away the fust of the 19th century, and their width influenced fashion for
the next 30 years.
The English drape, which had an acreage of material 'draping' from the new,
broader-shouldered jacket, arrived early in the 1930s. Peaked lapels, narrow
hips and wide, tapering trousers in confident chalkstripes or Glenurquhart
check contrived against nature to bless the wearer with a V-shaped manliness
to help defy the Depression. Edward VIII, then the Prince of Wales, wore it
to perfection, and where the prince led, Hollywood dandies - Astaire, Gable,
Cooper, Grant - followed. So powerful was the influence of the celluloid
celebrities that the English drape had become the American drape by the end
of the decade.
Then came the second world war. The US emerged in winning form. Confident as
hell, the all-American male swaggered out of it even more manly, rolling his
super-wide, extra-padded gaberdine shoulders, rubbing his hands together and
looking forward to an endless summer of profitable world domination. But a
few icy gusts from the cold war in the 1950s put paid to that idea. He
withdrew into a Brooks Brothers grey flannel suit - a buttoned-up,
button-down, Ivy League corporate man.
In the UK in the post-war ration years, only two sections of society could
afford to dress up: toffs and spivs. The spivs went directly for the
Technicolor American look, a strictly new money concoction of wide-boy
shoulders, big lapels, lots of drape, hand-painted ties and Al Capone
two-tone shoes. It was flash, brash and bought for cash at Cecil Gee's shop
on the Charing Cross Road. At the opposite, less colourful end of the social
spectrum, former Guards officers went to Savile Row for a long, narrow,
nipped and tucked interpretation of Edwardiana, complete with bowlers,
carnations and canes. Both styles faded away when rationing was stopped, but
they revealed the beginnings of two enduring influences: a love affair with
the US and the first stirrings of nostalgia.
The most significant style of the 1950s, however, looked only forward. It
emerged from Italy's post-war ricostruzione, which grabbed the attention of
the young. This was the Italy of coffee bars, Lambrettas and sharp haircuts.
Suits, as pioneered by the Roman tailor Gaetano Savini Brioni, were edited
to the limit: shortish jackets, sloping natural shoulders, narrow trousers
without pleats or turn-ups and horizontal pockets, like jeans. All very
novel, but, more importantly, made in lightweight materials: silk shantung
or mohair. From now on the heavyweights would struggle. The Italians had
burst on to the men's fashion scene, and they have since been front-runners.
In the late 1950s, the French designer Pierre Cardin set about replacing the
squatness of the Italian suit with a longer, cylindrical, fitted look, and
it was this that became the standard silhouette of the 1960s. Lapels all but
disappeared from vented jackets; skimpy, low-hipped trousers hung shy of
shoes. In the age of youth, grown men were letting their hair down and
wearing boys' suits. Worse was to come: by the early 1970s, beneath artfully
teased feather cuts, they were wearing girls' suits. The exaggeratedly
waisted jacket with deep vents, no shoulders to speak of, aircraft carrier
lapels and dangerously tight trousers flaring out over a pair of brown and
cream platform boots, looked as laughable as it reads.
Back in the office, there was a particular black and pale grey mohair Tonik
cloth which looked snappy on a 17-year-old in 1967, but seemed like greasy,
overcooked Bacofoil by 1978, on a 40-year-old.
The Hirondelle-bottle silhouette of the 1970s was discarded amid the
infighting between preppies, punks, rockabillies, Sloane rangers and a dozen
other clans. But of all these factions it is perhaps the yuppies who most
summed up the spirit of the 1980s - with an aggressive, inverted wedge-shape
silhouette, small slicked head, big shoulders (new money again), big chests,
no vents, loose pleated trousers, with turn-ups and let's-get-to-work
braces. Something Italian, like Armani, something bossy, like BOSS. There
was no messing with the American loafers or the Brooks Brothers shirt, but
the Hermes tie with the witty motif showed, hey, a sense of irony.
There is no doubt that the suit will see the century out, and probably the
next one, too. Reviled, revered, revived, revamped, unstructured,
deconstructed, oversized and understated, it is currently being slimmed down
and softened up in the Edwardian manner: archaic but evocative in blackish
Cheviot. Whatever fashion dictates, it will have said it all before.
Nevertheless, if you want to look your best and remain totally invisible at
the same time, wear a suit.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
