<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: Trooping the colour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THERE IS NO doubt about it
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the glamour-puss is back. Here comes the femme fatale, a dead ringer for
Gianni Versace's Cyber Princess, teetering on her vertiginous heels, all
dressed up in a languid, bias-cut slip of a dress and an elegant string of
pearls. It is a look that only truly comes into its own at night, and it
needs the make-up to match.
A full, red mouth is the hallmark of this winter's face. lf you buy nothing
else, buy a red lipstick. Reds, as every woman knows, come in many shades,
and the rule of thumb is to take time and trouble to find the one that suits
your mood: rich, vibrant and glossy for when you're feeling vampish; the
barest of lip stains for when you want to show some restraint; or a deep
vermilion for when you want to throw caution to the wind. For the
faint-hearted, deep reds can be diluted with lip balm. For the bold and
confident, a lip liner should be used first - to create a perfect lip shape
and then the chosen red should be applied with a lip brush. There are shades
of red for every skin tone.
Go for a dramatic look in the evening. Draw a smoky line inside and outside
the edge of the eye. For the really daring, coloured eyeshadow - even bright
China blue, until recently a definite no-no - looks new and fresh.
Every cosmetic house worth its lip gloss has come up with the foundations,
the blushers and the colours that this winter's face requires - at a price.
You could spend as little as pounds 29.70 at the least expensive house or as
much as pounds 219 on the basic essentials for the new haute chic look.
Here, we chart the price of the look from four cosmetic houses.
