<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: Some enchanted evening
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This winter, the fashion wheel has turned - decisively. From the glossy
pages of the world's most authoritative fashion bibles to the windows of the
smallest high street store, a new sort of woman is being celebrated. Out go
shapeless shrouds and dreary shifts. Out go combat boots and pale faced
waifs. In come shapely curves and clothes that flatter, high-gloss make-up
and well-groomed tresses. Womanly fashion is here again. It is quite all
right - essential even - to be grown-up.
The best, the most creative, of its designers have perceived, almost before
it happened, a shift in the zeitgeist. Fashion, as sensitive a barometer of
social change as any mainstream art, is functioning as it should.
A society grown tired of the swankiness of the 1980s, exhausted by the
confusing images of the early 1990s and weary of the drabness of grunge is
more than ready for something new.
With the worst of the recession behind us and a renewed sense of optimism in
the air, it is time to dress up again, time for artifice, time to practise
the age-old arts of seduction and, above all, time to have a little
light-hearted fun.
Nowhere is the new-style glamour more evident than after dark, and then it
comes in many guises. Sometimes it emerges tongue-in-cheek, sometimes it is
straight parody and sometimes just sheer knock-out beautiful. Everywhere
there are references to glamour's golden age, the heyday of Hollywood and
the celluloid sirens with their permanent waves, painted nails and faces.
At other times, it plays with covering up beautiful women in traditional
men's clothing, reminding us irresistibly of Marlene Dietrich in The Blue
Angel, or Katharine Hepburn in Sylvia Scarlett, or Yves Saint Laurent's
hard-edged tuxedos of the 1970s.
For dedicated followers of the fashion scene the old glamour standbys are
there: the sheer stockings with short, short skirts, the stiletto heels with
mannish trouser suits, the careful grooming, the deliberate air of artifice.
Most importantly, the look this winter is one that each can adapt to her
own. Here, on these pages, are some of the many ways to get all dressed up
when you have somewhere to go.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P23   Apparel and Other Textile Products.
    P56   Apparel and Accessory Stores.
</IN>
