<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: Princess without a realm - A princess by
birth, Olga of Greece is as comfortable leading the life of an art student
as being a member of the cosmopolitan circle of royalty. Jane Mulvagh talks
to her about how she reconciles these different worlds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE MULVAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Princess Olga de Grece says her name in America, people think she is a
perfume. 'Attitudes to royalty depend on where you are,' she says. 'In
America no one really gives a jot. In Europe, on the other hand, which has a
history, of royalty. People give you more of their time because they're
curious about you.'
In her own land, her rank would be unrecognised because in 1974 a referendum
was passed stripping all the royals of their titles. However, even if she
wished - and she does not wish it Olga could not escape the lustre of royal
birth. So how does a girl who is handsome, clever and rich conduct herself
in the two very different worlds of being a student and a princess?
She knows that sometimes she is invited to a party 'just because of my name.
This gives me the chance to meet interesting people whom I wouldn't
otherwise come across'. The duality of her different lives amuses her.
'Obviously I am the same person and don't change when moving from one world
to another. I look at any experience from a distance, taking a step back
from it.'
She admits to exploiting her title on occasion to help a charity. But she is
glad that 'unlike the English royals, I don't have duties and obligations
and I haven't had to live a courtly life. I get the best of both worlds. On
the one hand, I live like a student in a studio in New York, and on the
other, I go to royal parties and interesting events.'
As the daughter of Prince Michael and Princess Marina and cousin of the
exiled King Constantine, Olga has enjoyed a privileged youth, spending her
first six years in her homeland. In 1977 her father's interests - he is a
historical novelist and her mother is a sculptor - took the family to Paris,
which has become their main home. 'I feel totaly Greek but since I have not
lived here for years, except for spending summers on Patmos, I somehow feel
out of touch with contemporary Greece.'
Being the product of a morganatic marriage, Olga believes that her
upbringing has been 'a nice balance between the artistic world of my mother
and the traditional royal values of my father'. She had a cosmopolitan and
multilingual education in England, France and America and went on to study
history at Princeton, then industrial design at Parsons School of Design in
New York and now she is about to start a post-graduate course in
architecture.
Olga takes care to behave like a modern royal, modern in the sense that she
carries her background with aplomb into her contemporary life. At the same
time she does not hide her heritage, 'though an older friend of the family
did explain that in the 1970s it was much more uncool to be a princess than
it is right now, in the 1990s'.
Apart from being a princess, Olga's beauty must help to keep the invitations
flowing. Some profiles cry out to be immortalised on canvas or in marble;
hers is so precise in line, her ivory complexion so faultless, that artists
and photographers alike are struck by her presence. Like a peregrine falcon,
her black-eyed and sharp-beaked features and unflinching directness of her
gaze suggest a triumph of composure over youthful anxiety. At 22, she has
the still beauty of a Sumerian sculpture or - a princess.
How does she feel about using this exiled rank to gain advantage in the
modern world? She concedes that her name helped her get her summer job at
Ettore Sottsass's architectural practice in Milan. 'But after that you have
to work twice as hard for people to take you seriously. Both my parents had
a hard time winning respect in the professional world.'
Olga is indebted to Sottsass because 'in his huge open-plan office I saw all
the elements of design - architecture, graphics, industrial design - and I
reaised I wanted to create in 3D.' Now, in her spare time she sculpts
brightly coloured clay objects, such as teapots, candlesticks and vases,
which are reminiscent of the pneumatic figures that Nikki de Saint-Phalle
used to do in the 1970s. Family friends started ordering them and so she set
up a small production line.
Apart from art and design, 'the other thing I absolutely love with a huge
passion is space' not terrestrial acres but the stars and the moon. When she
applied to Princeton she wrote that she wanted to major in 'a course that
does not exist - Lunar Architecture. Amazingly enough they accepted me,
which gives them some credit for imagination] You look up into the stars and
realise how small you and the earth really are and how vast this subject
is.'
After graduating she applied to National Aeronautics and Space Adminstration
(NASA) to work on The Search for ExtraTerrestrial Intelligence Project. 'It
was a new Project started two or three years ago. Sadly, they only needed
qualified scientists and there were no odd jobs going.
'My love of space is not necessarly a physical thing. I would think twice
before zipping into a space shuttle and going to the moon but, one day, I
hope to be able to contribute to space research. As a designer and architect
there's not much one can do yet but, in time, they'll need architects on the
moon.'
She may not be going to the moon but Olga does travel a great deal and every
Christmas her father takes the family on a cultural journey to India, Bali
or Russia to familiarise them all with other cultures. But Olga confesses
that she finds constant travel unnerving. 'I am not one of those people who
likes to keep travelling all their lives without settling.' Instead she
feels great sympathy with the Russian novelist Goncharov's character
Oblomov, 'because he just lies in bed all day. It's so wonderful. You can't
do that any more, that belongs to a bygone era. His whole life was passed
away in bed - it's something I'd love to do. Nor can you behave with the
decadence of Huysmans's hero in Against Nature.'
In her dress, Olga says she always strives for simplicity which she enlivens
with a sense of drama. At five foot, nine inches tall, Olga's womanly figure
would overpower frills and folderols, while her sense of visual drama
prevents her from taking refuge in the safe option of a little black dress.
'I simply don't want a little black dress. My wardrobe isn't composed of
things that are useful for all occasions. It would probably make my life
easier but I'm never tempted to buy such things.'
Instead, her high-impact taste favours clean lines, Zurbaran's (the Spanish
devotional painter) colours - vermilion, terracotta, pewter, Prussian blue,
lemon yellow - and real jewels. I asked her what she would like to have in
her wardrobe and she did not hesitate. 'A huge pearl necklace - real, of
course; a huge embroidered dress, not something you would wear ever day -
perhaps like one of those Medici women in a Bronzino portrait; and generally
things that you can't find in shops.'
When she does shop, she favours Jil Sander's Germanic minimalism and Prada's
simplicity and shoes by Chrstian Louboutin, who recently named a pair of
Louis-heeled satin mules after her. Evening gowns are made by her friend
Maria Synder in New York. By day she creates a counterpoint to her
femininity with white shirts, buff suede jeans from Joseph and black
polo-necks. By night, think Old Master paintings in rich dramatic shapes and
Florentine richness and you've got the picture.
Feminist-motivated androgyny is anathema to Olga. 'I'm definitely for
enhancing your femininity; there's no reason to hide it. You might as well
use it.'
As to political feminism, she is somewhat ambivalent. 'I am so used to
living in New York where being a feminist can often imply that you're rather
militant about it. But I'm of a new generation. I'm happy with the
advancement and, thankfully, I'm a beneficiary of all those doors that have
been opened by others - but I'm definitely not a militant.'
Olga is a pragmatist and carries herself with composure and a maturity
beyond her years. Her composure is rooted in her affection for the Orthodox
church and her belief in God, combined with worldly realism. Her charm,
which wins invitations as much as her royal blood and arresting beauty, is
her teasing mirth and her ability to enliven any group of people she is
with. Olga has an attractive serenity, a quality I noticed when I first met
her aged 18. It lends her the aura of a modern and playful caryatid.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-8607</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-FALDBAGRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941119
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 NOV 94 / How To Spend It: Fashion Focus - At the Paris spring/summer
1995 collections, the FT conducted its annual survey. Brenda Polan
elaborates on the results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRENDA POLAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Humanity is notoriously torn between the comfort of the familiar and the
thrill of novelty. And even for the most susceptible (and experienced)
followers of fashion it is not unusual to perceive a conflict between
creativity and wearability. The great leaps of imagination which give us new
and appropriate ways to dress have all initially found their dismissive
opponents before gaining complete acceptance and supplanting all that went
before. We often need a little period of adjustment. In fashion-speak it is
called 'getting your eye in'.
This helps to explain why many of the industry experts who participated in
the Financial Times survey of the Paris collections for spring/summer 1995
voted one designer most creative but intended to buy their wardrobe from
another.
On the strength of October's showings, Jean Paul Gaultier was acclaimed, by
a substantial margin, the most creative designer of the season. In second
place was Britain's Vivienne Westwood, followed, fairly closely, by her
compatriot, John Galliano, the Japanese designers, Issey Miyake and Rei
Kawakubo of the Comme des Garcons label and then by the two Frenchmen,
Claude Montana and Christian Lacroix. The picture is slightly confused by
the admirers of Karl Lagerfeld. His own-label range, Lagerfeld, placed
eighth and his collection for Chanel tied with Lolita Lempicka for ninth
place, but, if you add up his percentage points, the number of experts
naming him most creative is the same as those nominating Galliano.
Interestingly, it was Lagerfeld's Chanel collection which was considered far
and away the most likely to be copied by the lower echelons of the fashion
industry worldwide. It was also the collection most likely to attract the
experts' hard-earned pennies. In this category Vivienne Westwood tied for
second place with Christian Dior (unranked for creativity), Jean Paul
Gaultier came sixth while, in between, was Lolita Lempicka (ninth in the
creativity ratings), and Chantal Thomass, a hardy survivor from the early
1980s.
If respondents appeared to neglect the designers who had shown the previous
week in Milan and London (and they could hardly take the Americans, who were
to show at the beginning of November, into consideration) then that is
because Paris is still the influential heart of fashion. With admirable
Gallic ruthlessness, Paris seduces the most imaginative of the rest of the
world's designers on to its schedule, gathering them to its otherwise stony
bosom with tenderness and passion. To watch the officers of the Chambre
Syndicale, the French industry's governing body, leading a standing ovation
for Issey Miyake is to understand that in Paris the nationhood of talent
takes precedence over nationalistic concerns with export figures.
When Denise Dubois, the achingly, 'Frenchly'-elegant head of its press
office, gazes with misty-eyed pride at a bowing Vivienne Westwood clad in
one of her own rigid bustles, you understand that a different kind of
chauvinism is at work. The great fashion innovators, whatever their place of
birth, belong to Paris.
The atmosphere of excited anticipation, of euphoric pleasure or desperate
disappointment which characterises these shows is unique to Paris. And when
Paris comes up with a season like this one, so full of drama, triumph and
disaster, beauty and perversity, passion and magic, even the accomplishments
of the Milanese faded into memories hard to revive. So when one interprets
the figures from this survey and discovers only minimal mentions for
designers showing in Italy and London, one has to offer them the comfort of
an explanation.
In the first FT survey (conducted in March during the Paris collections for
autumn/winter 1994), Giorgio Armani topped the polls for commercial success
and long-term influence, but for creativity, (the focus of the current
survey), he came eleventh. Ahead of him were Westwood, Miyake, Gaultier,
Yohji Yamamoto, Kawakubo, Galliano, Martin Margiela, Romeo Gigli, And
Demeulemeester, Karl Lagerfeld and Jil Sander.
So what do the great creative designers of the mid 1990s have in common that
impels even those who would not wear their product to acknowledge their
pre-eminence? I recently asked one of the brighter supermodels, Kate Moss,
to name her favourite designers. She dutifully mentioned Calvin Klein, her
biggest employer, and added Westwood, of course, and then her face lit up
with that wicked litile grin which so devastates photographers. 'And John
Galliano because he's always got a story. John tells you a story, like
you're the romantic young widow of a very rich older man and you've just
come back from the funeral and all the other mourners have gone and suddenly
you can't stand being alone in your empty mansion and you hit the town in
your widow's weeds. And you can be someone. It's so great ..'
It may not always be that well thought out, but many of the great creative
designers have a story. They are not actually costuming a mini-drama of
their own creation but instead they evoke a mood, a moment, an identity
which finds a response in the way women, at that moment, imagine themselves.
Jean Paul Gaultier, for instance, started his carnival of a show by
presenting what appeared to be a potted history of 20th-century dress, from
Edwardian sugar-icing elegance to space-age micro-dresses. But, lo, we were
not, after all, in a museum but in a Hollywood wardrobe department. And as
the carousel music sped up, Gaultier's heroine, heavily-lidded,
glossy-mouthed and nightclub pallid, reappeared in an archivist's nightmare
of chronologically mismatched pieces, dissolving the process of logical time
and inspiring chuckles of delight from his audience.
Of course, to women who just want flattering, sensible, smart clothes, this
can all seem overly cerebral, elitist, pretentious and precious. But out of
a joyous exercise such as Gaultier's come the new shapes and
textures,combinations and contrasts which will define the moment and dictate
what we all wear.
Fashion does not always achieve such vitality. The times must demand it
before the designers can feel a need that must be answered. In the mid 1990s
we are lucky (or not, if you don't give a damn and love your shellsuit) to
have so many extraordinarily creative designers in fashion. Chanel may have
had Schiaparelli as a despised companion and rival in experiment, but Dior
had to go it alone and Yves Saint Laurent risked his sanity before a
generation of designers accepted his creative lead.
Today, there is a comradeship of creativity. Westwood, Galliano, Miyake,
Kawakubo, Lacroix, Yamamoto, Margiela, Marongiu (when he is on form), Ozbek
(ditto), Mugler and Lagerfeld all approach their craft in an analytical,
deconstructionist way, using the work of all their predecessors as a
springboard for ideas. Their points of focus differ, of course. Westwood may
explore extreme historical concepts of female beauty, styles and aspects of
dress, such as the bustle, or cleavage-contorting corsetry that caricature
women's 'Erotic Zones' (the title of her show). Yamamoto may compulsively,
deconstruct the kimono, the garment his nation wore, unchanging, for
centuries, and then reconstruct it in stunning and startling marriages with
aspects of western dress. Miyake may push the beauty and functionality of
fabric beyond all boundaries, reconciling comfort, flattery and
breathtakingly magical effects in defiance of the limits of the possible.
But whatever their focus, they all simultaneously expand our understanding
of the past as expressed through dress and enrich our present with amusing
and beautiful choices for getting dressed tomorrow.
Even Karl Lagerfeld, most copied and, it appears, most coveted, is an
irreverent deconstructionist. He is best known for deconstructing and
reconstructing (in a manner that many deem extraordinarily vulgar) the
life's work of Coco Chanel. For those of us who hero-worship Chanel, thc
vitality of the result is clouded by a frisson of lese majeste but as Karl
himself said to a packed lecture hall at the Sorbonne, 'My taste is so bad,
it is good.' Well, sometimes. What his poor taste expresses is a healthy
dissent from the stale, the safe, the overly respected. In the late 1980s,
Lagerfeld used his licence at Chanel to pander to the status-hunger of the
times while simultaneously, mocking it. He broke every rule the sober-sided
Coco ever made. This demonstrates that making an icon of the century's
greatest fashion iconoclast was a pretty silly move - even if she, in her
later years, would have approved of the accolade.
It is, however, the authority of the Chanel name, the icon-quality, which
makes Lagerfeld's line so imitated and so covetable. Within the narrow
confines of the fashion world, Lagerfeld has an impressive track record;
outside it, Coco's name still sells and sells. The glamour conjured by her
name still comforts, still reassures.
Which is what we need now. So, as the emphasis of fashion turns once more
towards formality, glamour and the joy of a little light-hearted,
self-conscious role-playing, the truly creative designers move in from the
fringe to oust the more conventional designers from centre stage. And this
season, as the FT survey shows; the man who summed up the spirit of 1995 was
Gaultier, and the woman was his posy, red-lipped, spike-heeled drama queen.
