For this Survey we canvassed the opinions of an international cross-section
of fashion editors, buyers and industry specialists attending the recent
spring/summer 1995 collections in Paris. They were asked to rate the
designers for 'creativity', and the collections they fund 'most promising',
'most covetable' and 'most likely to be copied'.
For our Top Ten lists we scored the number of votes for each designer as a
percentage of the number of respondents. There was surprising consensus of
opinion within different age groups and between nationalities despite slight
variations. Respondents in their 20s put Gaultier, Westwood and Galliano at
the top of their lists for 'creativity', with Miyake in fifth place,
meriting only a third of Gaultier's score, while those in their 30s and 40s
put Miyake on top, with Galliano and Gaultier close behind. Men and women
alike thought Gaultier the 'most creative' but women placed Miyake a
decisive second while men ranked him fifth. Perhaps surprisingly, the French
rated Westwood the 'most creative' (with Gaultier a close second), while the
British reversed the order (but only by a few votes).
In the category of collections 'most likely to be copied', Chanel's strong
lead reflected an overwhelming French vote, although only the British
respondents had another candidate for the top slot (Westwood). There was
also a broad unanimity about the 'most covetable' collections with Chanel,
Westwood and Dior leading the pack.
</TEXT>
