<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / GM files lawsuit to block recall of 6m trucks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Motors yesterday filed a lawsuit against the US administration and
Mr Federico Pena, transport secretary, in an effort to block a forced recall
of an estimated 6m of its pick-up trucks.
The US's biggest vehicle maker had threatened the action last month, when Mr
Pena first said he planned to push for the recall. GM turned down a request
for a voluntary recall made by the US transport authorities 18 months ago.
The company's legal action marks an intensification of the fight over the
vehicles, which critics say are liable to burst into flames when involved in
side-on collisions.
GM said yesterday it had filed a complaint in the federal court for the
eastern district of Michigan against Mr Pena, the US transport department
and the national highway traffic safety administration, on whose research Mr
Pena based his recall decision. The suit seeks an injunction against the
recall, and a declaratory judgment overturning the decision.
Mr Thomas Gottschalk, the carmaker's general counsel, said the complaint
'directly challenges the secretary's position that he can disregard federal
motor vehicle safety standards and retroactively require the redesign of
older cars and trucks which unquestionably met the safety standards and
which perform as safely or more safely than most other vehicles on the road
today.'
Ford and Chrysler have joined GM in criticising Mr Pena's decision. The
three carmakers argue that the attempted recall throws US car safety
standards into confusion, since it applies to vehicles which passed federal
standards when they were sold.
</TEXT>
