<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures moved lower, but there was little real sense of
direction to the session and trading volume was low, writes Jeffrey Brown.
The FT-SE 100 December contract was standing at 3,136 when pit trading came
to an end, down 16 points, eroding some of the advance of 79 points recorded
over the previous three days.
At this level the premium to the cash market was 9 points, while the fair
value premium was just above 7 points.
Trading was mostly uneventful. Two-way business was thin at best and dealing
sizes narrowed sharply. Contracts dealt tailed off steeply from the high
levels of the previous two sessions.
Volume was 10,522 contracts, but more than 3,000 of these were pushed
through in the final 30 minutes of official trading. Some 16,000 lots were
traded on Wednesday, while Tuesday's number came close to 20,000.
The fitful nature of the day was reflected in a trading arc of 40 points,
with the December contract fluctuating between a low of 3,125 and a best of
3,165.
Traded option volume also declined, moving down from Wednesday's 56,430
contracts to 30,506. FTSE and Euro FT-SE trading accounted for less than
20,000 lots.
HSBC was the most active stock option with a modest 800 lots, followed by
Barclays and Vodafone.
</TEXT>
