<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Auction prices fluctuated only narrowly this week, with the Australian
tendency slightly firmer, taking the market indicator 5c higher to 795c/kg.
New Zealand and this week's Bradford sale of Scottish wool showed mixed
changes, with some British carpet categories definitely dearer but the
market in general no more than firm, The main factor affecting prices was
currency, with the US dollar rising after the interest rate rise. Close
connection with the currencies of the main wool producing countries means
that major international wool users are paying more. The added price
increases related to currency is not helping the flow of trade. Longer term
wool supply and demand calculations continue to stress the likelihood of
shortages in the earlier months of 1995, and maintain a firm view of the
price outlook.
