<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / International Company News: Hewlett-Packard tops
expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hewlett-Packard's share price reached a 10-year high yesterday when the
computer and electronics company reported even stronger-than-expected
fourth-quarter results. Earnings rose 60 per cent on a 23 per cent increase
in revenues.
H-P, the second-largest US computer company after IBM, is setting the pace
in the market for 'client-server' networks of computers, and also dominates
the rapidly-growing market for printers used with personal computers.
Fourth-quarter sales and order growth was 'outstanding and well balanced
across all geographies', said Mr Lew Platt, chairman, president and chief
executive.
Net earnings for the quarter, to end-October, were Dollars 476m or Dollars
1.83 a share, up from Dollars 298m or Dollars 1.18, in the same period last
year. (Earlier this year H-P changed its earnings per-share calculations to
include employee stock options, increasing the effective number of shares
outstanding by about 6m to 260m.)
Net revenue for the quarter was Dollars 7bn, an increase of 23 per cent over
the same quarter last year. US sales were Dollars 3.3bn,up 20 per cent,
while international sales rose 26 per cent to Dollars 3.7bn.
H-P said new orders booked during the fourth quarter were valued at Dollars
6.9bn, an increase of 25 per cent over the same period last year. The order
growth rate signals continuing strong performance in fiscal 1995.
As a percentage of net revenue, cost of goods sold rose to 62.2 per cent
from 61.4 per cent in last year's fourth quarter. However, the ratio of
operating expenses to revenues declined to 26.8 per cent from 30.2 per cent.
For the full year, H-P reported a 36 per cent increase in net earnings to
Dollars 1.6bn from Dollars 1.2bn. Net earnings per share were Dollars 6.14,
up from Dollars 4.65. Net revenues for the year rose 23 per cent to Dollars
25bn from Dollars 20.3bn.
Mr Platt said H-P was starting 1995 in a strong competitive position, but
that 'given our size, and the fact that our growth rates have exceeded those
of many markets in which we compete, we're not assuming that our recent
order-growth rates will continue'.
In mid-session yesterday H-P shares were trading at Dollars 101 3/4 , but
fell back to Dollars 100 by the close for a net gain on the day of Dollars 1
1/2.
</TEXT>
