<DATE>941118
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Carmakers focus on Barclay twins - AFGH
deal unites three secretive entrepreneurs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sale of Automotive Financial Group Holdings, one of the biggest motor
retailer groups in Britain, has brought together three of the most secretive
entrepreneurs operating in the UK.
The buyers, the Barclay brothers, the reclusive identical twins David and
Frederick, take secrecy to extremes. Shying away from all publicity, they
operate their business empire from Monaco. A year ago they added a new
hideaway, the Channel Island of Brecqhou situated between Guernsey and Sark,
which they are busy converting into their own island fortress.
The seller is Mr Octav Botnar, the 81-year-old entrepreneur, who has made a
villa in the mountains near Geneva the base for his dwindling business
operations, ever since a warrant was issued for his arrest by the Inland
Revenue in January, 1992.
The Barclay twins' strategy for AFGH, their first foray into the UK retail
motor industry, is still to be revealed. Their progress will be watched
carefully, however, by some of the world's leading carmakers - most notably
Fiat, Renault, Peugeot and Citroen - which are suddenly discovering this
week, that several of the dealerships operating their franchise in the UK
are under new and mysterious owership.
The UK's motor retail sector is already undergoing a far-reaching
restructuring with a spate of takeovers in the last two years, as the
leading groups led by Lex Service and Inchcape have swallowed up smaller
operators.
Few of the shockwaves reverberating through the sector have been bigger,
however, than those created by the businesses controlled by Mr Octav Botnar,
namely Automotive Financial Group Holdings, now owned by the Barclay
brothers, and its sister company, Nissan UK Holdings.
Only four years ago the Automotive and Financial Group dealer network
totalled about 180 outlets, selling exclusively new Nissan vehicles. Today,
it has no Nissan dealerships - Nissan Motor, the Japanese carmaker, has
established its own UK dealer network starting from scratch in 1992 - while
AFG has been transformed into a multifranchise group with about 70 outlets.
In these four years, Mr Botnar's business empire has been rocked first by
the upheaval of a tumultuous legal battle with Nissan, Japan's second
largest carmaker, which stripped Nissan UK of its franchise with effect from
the end of 1991, and secondly by the corporation tax fraud investigation by
the Inland Revenue.
With the sale of AFGH Mr Botnar appears to have decided to throw in the
towel and to cease trying to exercise remote control of one of the UK's
biggest dealer groups by telephone from Switzerland.
He faces a battle with the Inland Revenue, however, over the other company
he controls, Nissan UK Holdings, about a Pounds 238m tax claim at its
wholly-owned subsidiary Nissan UK. NUKH's latest annual report says the
company will 'contest the assessments in the strongest possible manner as
being without foundation'.
Mr Botnar has controlled as chairman and managing director both NUKH and
AFGH, but their ultimate ownership has remained unclear.
Immediate majority ownership of NUKH is held by European Motor Vehicles
Corporation, registered in Panama, which has a 71.5 per cent stake, while a
stake of the same size in AFGH has been held by GF International Investments
and Finance, registered in the Bahamas. Both companies are controlled by the
same group of trustees of a settlement made by Mr Botnar with his shares in
1974. The identity of the trustees has never been revealed, although a
condition of Mr Botnar's transfer of his shares to the trust, according to
NUK, was that he should remain chairman and chief executive 'for life with
full powers'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
