<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Hilton clears way for sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Hilton Hotels, the US hotel and casino group, shot up Dollars 10
to Dollars 67 7/8 yesterday - a gain of more than 17 per cent - after the
company effectively put itself on the market for the second time in five
years.
It said it had engaged Smith Barney, the Wall Street investment bank, to
advise on a number of strategic alternatives including a possible break-up
or sale of the company, a merger with another business, or a share
repurchase programme.
The company said the purpose of the move was to enhance shareholder value,
but would not elaborate further.
Hilton Hotels owns, manages or franchises Hilton hotels in the US, operates
several more hotels overseas under the Conrad name, and has extensive gaming
operations, mostly in Las Vegas. Its market valuation at yesterday's closing
price was Dollars 3.3bn.
The company once operated Hilton hotels around the world, but it sold Hilton
International in 1966. That company is now owned by Ladbroke.
Some 24.5 per cent of Hilton Hotels' stock is controlled by Mr Barron
Hilton, the company's chairman and chief executive. A Hilton family
charitable foundation, the Conrad N. Hilton Fund, controls another 8.6 per
cent.
Mr Barron Hilton invited offers for the company in 1989, but a year later he
was forced to take it off the auction block because no serious bidders
emerged.
Recently, Hilton's gaming operations have been suffering from tough
competition in the key Las Vegas market, but the hotel division has been
performing well. Recovery in the US economy has lifted room rates and
occupancy levels, and last month Hilton reported a 32 per cent increase in
net income to Dollars 27m in the third quarter.
Mr David Wolfe, an analyst at Oppenheimer, a Wall Street brokerage, said
Hilton appeared to be taking advantage of an upswing in the hotel industry
to get a fresh valuation on the company. 'The environment for the hotel
industry is such that they can see an opportunity to get a good price for at
least one part of the business,' he said.
Possible buyers could include ITT, US owner of the Sheraton hotel chain, or
and Ladbroke of the UK, because both have been seeking to expand their
gambling interests.
</TEXT>
