<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Actuaries attack plan on pension solvency standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government efforts to win employers' backing for pension reforms have been
set back by the refusal of actuaries to endorse proposed minimum solvency
standards for pension schemes.
Members of the actuaries' professional body say the latest proposals are so
weak that it would be better to have no minimum requirement at all.
The government had hoped to give greater security to pension scheme members
while not raising employers' costs significantly. Wide-ranging proposals,
including a minimum solvency standard, were put forward by the Goode
Committee, the government's advisory panel, in September last year.
But in recent months there has been pressure from employers to water down an
earlier minimum solvency proposal on the grounds that it would increase
pension costs sharply.
Actuaries, who assess the probability that pension funds will be able to
meet their obligations, say that if the current proposals are enacted, they
will lull scheme members into a false sense of security over whether
promised pensions will be paid.
'This would defeat the purpose of what the solvency standard is trying to
achieve,' said Mr Nigel O'Sullivan, partner at consulting actuaries Bacon
and Woodrow. 'Minimum solvency would be illusory.'
Following an acrimonious meeting last week of the pensions board of the
Institute and Faculty of Actuaries, which sets professional standards, Mr
Paul Thornton, its chairman, wrote to the Department of Social Security to
express unhappiness with the proposals.
Mr Thornton said in his letter that the profession would use the proposed
standard only if ordered to do so by the government. He said yesterday that
while the government proposal was considered by many to be too weak to
really guarantee solvency, 'the political requirement is to deliver a
solvency standard'.
Some actuaries say the proposed minimum solvency standard would force them
to issue a qualified opinion for every pension scheme they certified as
solvent, a move akin to accountants qualifying corporate accounts.
Specifically, schemes will be able to meet the solvency standard by applying
their holdings in equities against their liabilities for pensioners who are
expected to live at least 10 years. Schemes at present count only gilt
holdings against liabilities to current pensioners because only these
securities ensure certainty of income in the short run.
French pension reform, Page 2
Compulsory saving urged, Page 9
</TEXT>
