<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Transatlantic sensationalism in televised courtrooms is less dangerous than
Euro-artiness, to judge by The Trial (9pm, BBC2). Wonderful opening titles,
faces from Central Casting - villains and eccentrics of Dickensian ripeness
 -then cut to Edinburgh, that Jekyll and Hyde beauty-queen of cities.
Scotland has blazed the trail in admitting courtroom cameras, and the first
in Nick Catliff's series is a glossy mix of filmic values and incongruous
tragedy. The petty crook accused of murder is first glimpsed, as serenely
suffering as a madonna, beautifully, airily lit. His advocate is as
sardonically rueful, fastidiously lugubrious, as Rumpole. One forgets this
is real. Of course, it's not live, so no rough edges: smoothly edited
eavesdroppings on accused and solicitor, lawyers discussing tactics; the
camera roams freely in prison and court. Only occasional phrases, the
post-verdict anti-climax and a woman sobbing off-screen remind us this is no
soap opera. Which is worse, the obscene carnival of OJ Simpson or this
anodyne style exercise?
</TEXT>
